---
import Article from '../../layouts/Article.astro';
import Fig from '../../components/Fig.astro';
import { SITE } from '../../lib/site';
import { getRebates } from '../../lib/data';
import { formatDateLong } from '../../lib/rebate';

const rebates = getRebates();

const description = `Who runs ${SITE.name}: ${SITE.operator}, WA-based. How we verify rebate figures, how we make money, and what we will never do.`;
---

<Article
  title={`About ${SITE.name}`}
  description={description}
  crumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'About' }]}
  updated="2026-07-12"
  verified={rebates.meta.lastVerified}
  showMiniBoard={true}
>
  <Fragment slot="toc">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#who">Who runs this</a></li>
      <li><a href="#why">Why it exists</a></li>
      <li><a href="#method">Verification methodology</a></li>
      <li><a href="#money">How we make money</a></li>
      <li><a href="#never">What we never do</a></li>
    </ul>
  </Fragment>

  <p>
    {SITE.name} is Australia’s independent solar and battery guide. We publish verified rebate and cost
    figures so household buyers can check a quote against primary sources — especially when the federal
    Cheaper Home Batteries Program changes on a legislated schedule.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who">Who runs this</h2>
  <p>
    The site is operated by <strong>{SITE.operator}</strong>, based in Western Australia. WA is not a
    coincidence: Synergy versus Horizon rules, DEBS export bands, and Perth install pricing are easy to
    get wrong from a generic national brochure. We write the national pages carefully and the WA pages
    with local depth on purpose.
  </p>
  <p>
    Contact: <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a> · <a href="/contact/">Contact form</a>.
    ABN: {SITE.abn}.
  </p>

  <h2 id="why">Why it exists</h2>
  <p>
    Rebate content on the open web goes stale every time the STC factor or tier rules move. After{' '} <Fig>1 May 2026</Fig>, flat-rate articles quietly misled anyone still reading them. We built a site
    where rates live in data files, pages stamp <Fig>{formatDateLong(rebates.meta.lastVerified)}</Fig>{' '}
    when we last checked, and every update is listed on <a href="/what-changed/">What changed</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Independence is the other half. Major quote marketplaces are now owned by energy retailers. We state
    that as fact on our compare pages and keep our own ownership simple: this is an information site run
    by {SITE.operator}, not a retailer subsidiary.
  </p>

  <h2 id="method">Verification methodology</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Primary sources first.</strong> Federal figures trace to DCCEEW / Clean Energy Regulator
      program materials. State rows link to the administering agency pages in our data files.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Dated stamps.</strong> Data-driven pages show a verified date from the data file, not a
      decorative “updated” guess.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Public changelog.</strong> Material rate or scheme edits get a dated entry with affected
      URLs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One calculator.</strong> Worked examples and the public calculator share{' '}
      <code>calculateFederalRebate</code> — no hand-edited dollar figures in article templates.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>AI-assisted drafting, human figure checks.</strong> Copy may be drafted with AI tools; every
      money figure is checked against the data files or primary source before publish. See{' '} <a href="/editorial-policy/">Editorial policy</a>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="money">How we make money</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Phase 1 (now):</strong> display advertising (including AdSense) and affiliate links. Affiliate
    links are marked <code>rel="sponsored"</code> and accompanied by a disclosure where they appear.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Phase 2 (possible later):</strong> a quote referral form that shares your details with
    quoting partners. That form already exists behind <a href="/quotes/">/quotes/</a> but is noindexed
    and kept out of the main nav until we switch it on. If and when lead referrals become a revenue line,
    we will say so here and in the privacy policy — we will not soft-pedal that leads may be sold.
  </p>

  <h2 id="never">What we never do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Sell placement inside editorial rankings or “best of” lists.</li>
    <li>Hide ownership or revenue relationships that readers need to weigh trust.</li>
    <li>Invent fixed state rebate dollars when the primary source only publishes a variable instrument.</li>
    <li>Use urgency theatre (“last chance!!”) around legislated step-downs — we publish the dates instead.</li>
  </ul>
</Article>
